data.name: paste_girl
data.message:
When you delete text, it is
saved in the unnamed register
(appropriately called "") as if it
was cut. Paste command uses
the unnamed register by default
so the following paste command
will paste the most recently
deleted text.

You can paste after the cursor's
position with 'p' or before
with 'P'.

data.name: registers_girl
data.message:
To fully utilize the cut and
paste mechanism, you should
know about registers!

Registers are where text is
stored. A register is denoted
by " followed by a single
character for the register's
name. For example "d is the
register named d, and "- is
the register named -.

There are a number of register
groups, each storing different
text. Type ':reg' to view registers.

data.name: linewise_paste_kid
data.message:
If the deletion is line-wise,
pasted text will be added either
above ('P') or below ('p') the
current line.

data.name: del_numbered_regs
data.message:
When you delete a line or more
(not a word, or a letter) the
deleted content is stored in
the numbered registers, "1 - "9.
The latest delete is stored in
"1, the one before it is in "2
and so on. When another line
is deleted, the text in "9 is
discarded, "9 gets the value
stored in "8 and so on.

data.name: specify_register_girl
data.message:
You can specify a register name
before a paste command to tell
VIM which register you would like
to paste from. For example, you
can use "2p to paste the line
that was deleted right before the
most recent delete.

Use ':reg' followed by a register's
name to see its content.

data.name: block_hole_girl
data.message:
If you want a delete operation
to have no effect whatsoever
on the registers, specify "_
(that's an underscore) as its
target register. "_ is called
the "Black Hole register" and
nothing is really stored into it.

data.name: unnamed_and_small_girl
data.message:
When you delete text that's
shorter than a line without
specifying a target register,
the deleted content is saved
in the 'small delete' register
named "- (That's a minus).
Text shorter than a line is
not saved into the numbered
registers.

data.name: named_registers_kid
data.message:
The named registers "a - "z
can be used before any delete,
yank (and in the future also
change or substitute) command.

When the upper-case version of
their name is used ("A - "Z), the
deleted text will be appended to
their existing content instead of
replacing it.

data.name: reg_0_girl
data.message:
"0 stores the last yanked
line (or more) if no other
register was specified.

It is very useful when you
yank something and then
want to delete a few things
without loosing the yanked
text.

data.name: yank_whole_lines_kid
data.message:
You can yank whole
lines with 'yy' or 'Y'.

Check out the help for
an example (:help yy).
